<br>
Mages : Pet classes should ask for summoned armor (PR shoulders and range slot as a MINIMUM if we are doing AE mobs, but also summoned armor of other types/slots) for their pets, as it enhances them.  Also ask for Muzzle for your pet, its an extra 10% haste.  Necros should NOT equip weapons on their pets if their pet is 56 or the 59 pet, as it has been shown to lessen the dmg a pet can do.  53 can have weapons, but it is recommended to only equip daggers if you desire.  I recommened no weapons at all for any level pet.<br>
<br>
Chanters should not be asked to haste necro pets unless mana is tight from feeding, as our necro haste has 55% or 65% haste (we have 2 pet augment spells) plus str and AC.  As far as Burnout, I believe the higher level burnout spells are better than chanter haste, but hey, im not a mage, ask one for sure...:)  Chanters should not be asked to rune pets, unless you provide the dot IMO, and if you are a necro, that you provide a couple taps of mana to the chanter as well.<br>
<br>
Cleric buffs : well simply put I ask for a Arm buff (Donals vambraces give lower level Heroism buff called Valor - HP and AC good), and if I have a dot and some extra mana, I ask them to symbol my pet, but ONLY if they have the time and others do not need.  Then as a necro, I usually drop 3 or more taps on them, as symbol is highly mana intensive.  If there are 6 clerics at a raid, I will frequently ask the lowest level cleric for the buffs, as they will likely not be bombarded with "aego" tells from tanks and the like.  If they have a donals hat (most clerics dont, and even if they do, its in the bank), I ask a hat buff too - pure ac is uba.<br>
<br>
Wizards : Yes, wizards are not entirely worthless as far as buffs go.  SS/Thurg/Kael boots drop a mana free dmg shield, and should be requested for pets.  It also adds fire resist, but remember the DS from the boots only lasts 2 mins.  Ask for it early, and to be done right before we engage.<br>
<br>
Druids : Dmg shield stacks with Wiz dmg shield.  Only ask if they have time.  If you have a spec pet, and ONLY if you have a spec pet, ask for sow on your pet if we are outdoors.  Why only a spec pet?  Cause its immune to fear, and other pets (unless maybe epic mage pets, i think they are immune to fear too) are not.  As a druid, dont sow a skeleton pet ever if we are engaging a AOE Fearing mob.<br>
<br>
Shamans : Common misconception is our pets need regen.  It would be nice, but shamans have much more to do then to regen our pets, and our pets regen fast enuf.  IMO leave shamans alone, except maybe for SOW if the druid is busy.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
A lot of you are like "yeah right, Ill buff a pet when hell freezes over, its just a freakin pet"   True, it is "just a pet".  But as I've said time and again, pets can do an insane amt of dmg over a long fight.  Pets are the most mana efficient dots in the game.  And many times, my pet has been in the top 6 to 10 dmg dealers on a mob.  So yeah, it may take some time, may take some mana (but I'll give it right back, I promise :)))) but buffing your pet before a large fight is a good idea, and for those extra few seconds, it could save the raid and kill the mob.<br>
